 :: Primitive data type is predefined so easy to code in compiler.

<.𝟐.> 𝙉𝙤𝙣-𝙋𝙧𝙞𝙢𝙞𝙩𝙞𝙫𝙚 𝘿𝙖𝙩𝙖 𝙩𝙮𝙥𝙚𝙨 -->>
        > It is created using classes and used to store complex objects.
        > It provide by the programmer. Creating by own.
        > It has 3 types.
              \/
               \> 1. String       2. Arrays       3. Object / User defined-class

:1: 𝑺𝒕𝒓𝒊𝒏𝒈𝒔 ::--
          >> A string is a sequence of character in Java.
          >> Single line strings are defined with double qoutes. (" ")
          >> Multiline strings are defined with triple-qoutes.(""" """)

    𝙹𝚊𝚟𝚊 𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 -->>
       class Main
       {
         public static void main(String []args)
         {
           String x = "Hello Java";
           String y = """
                     Hello Java
                     Easy to Code
                     Code in IntelliJ """;

           System.out.println(x);
           System.out.println(y);
          }
        }

:2: 𝑨𝒓𝒓𝒂𝒚 ::--
      >> Collection of similar elements.
      >> Get the index of array List.

   𝙹𝚊𝚟𝚊 𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 -->>
        class Main
        {
          public static void main(String []args)
          {
            int[] x = {1,2,3,4,5};     
            String[] y = {"Hii" , "Hello"};

            System.out.println(x[0]);
            System.out.println(x[3]);
            System.out.println(y[1]);
           }
         }

 :3: 𝑶𝒃𝒋𝒆𝒄𝒕 -->>
      >> Custom types created using the class keyword.

 𝙹𝚊𝚟𝚊 𝙲𝚘𝚍𝚎 -->>
     class Main 
     {
        public static void main(String[] args) 
        {
           // Object example
           Person person = new Person("Alice", 30);

           System.out.println(person.name);
           System.out.println(person.age);
        }
    }

    // Class used for non-primitive example
    class Person 
    {
      String name;
       int age;

       // Constructor
       Person(String name, int age) 
       {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
       }
     }


